Here's a complete example of an MCP server wrapping a REST API:

---

**Program.cs** — stdio transport with DI:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: Log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC transport
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient("WeatherApi", client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.weather.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

**WeatherTools.cs** — tool class with constructor injection:

```csharp
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

[McpServerToolType]
public class WeatherTools(IHttpClientFactory httpFactory, ILogger<WeatherTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Get the current weather forecast for a city.")]
    public async Task<string> GetForecast(
        [Description("City name, e.g. 'Seattle'")] string city,
        [Description("Unit: 'metric' or 'imperial'")] string units = "metric",
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching forecast for {City}", city);
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var response = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/forecast?city={Uri.EscapeDataString(city)}&units={units}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Get weather alerts for a geographic region.")]
    public async Task<string> GetAlerts(
        [Description("Latitude of the location")] double latitude,
        [Description("Longitude of the location")] double longitude,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var client = httpFactory.CreateClient("WeatherApi");
        var response = await client.GetStringAsync(
            $"/alerts?lat={latitude}&lon={longitude}",
            cancellationToken);
        return response;
    }
}
```

---

## How DI Works for MCP Tools

The SDK resolves dependencies automatically via two mechanisms:

| Style | How it works |
|-------|-------------|
| **Constructor injection** (non-static class) | The class is instantiated per-request; DI services go in the primary constructor. Register services in `Program.cs` normally (`AddHttpClient`, `AddSingleton`, etc.). |
| **Method parameter injection** (static class) | DI services appear as method parameters alongside tool parameters. The SDK distinguishes them from tool inputs — DI types never appear in the JSON schema sent to the LLM. |

**What's auto-injected (never in schema):**
- `CancellationToken` — cooperative cancellation
- `IMcpServer` — server instance for notifications
- `IProgress<ProgressNotificationValue>` — report progress
- Any type registered in the DI container (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, custom services)

Only parameters decorated with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM as tool inputs. Everything else is injected by the framework.
